 their meanings. \u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003ci\u003eWomen Making History\u003c\/i\u003e shows that Helaine Victoria Press’s cards, like the movement from which they emanated, were dynamic and participatory. They were, in short, a multidirectional, open ended, rhetorically evolving process of transforming feminist consciousness. The print edition includes many images from the press’s records, and the digital edition offers additional images plus audio and video clips from press participants.\u003cbr\u003e This is the first book to demonstrate the relationships between the feminist art movement, the women in print movement, and the scholars studying women’s history. Readers will be drawn to both the large quantity of illustrative materials and the theoretical framework of the book, as it provides an expanded understanding of rhetorical multimodality. Scholars of gender and women’s studies, art history, media studies, and the history of rhetoric, as well as members of the public with interests in feminism, Lesbian feminist culture, postcards, fine letterpress printing, and papermaking will be inspired by this richly produced history.\u003cbr\u003e \u003cbr\u003e\u003cb\u003eAbout the authors\u003c\/b\u003e\u003cbr\u003e Julia M. Allen is professor emerita of English at Sonoma State University.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003eJocelyn H. Cohen is an artist, arborist and co-founder of Helaine Victoria Press, Inc.\u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.12737267\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.12737267","language":"eng","modified":"2024-03-06T09:19:02Z","published":"2023-01-01","publisher":"Lever Press","subject":"HISTORY / Women"},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/h415pd243/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/h415pd243/download","type":"application/epub