003e, the editors also include excerpts from rarely-translated letters published in an early modern gazette in response to the novel. These features enable a new generation of readers to grasp the seventeenth-century public’s reaction to Lafayette’s work.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003eDrawing on the affordances of the digital format to promote multilingualism and humanistic inquiry, the edition simultaneously encourages active engagement with the specificities of a particular language and culture. This project results from a collaboration between four professors who teach at liberal arts colleges and argues for critical approaches to digital technologies to celebrate a classic text.  \u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.12629286\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.12629286","language":["frc","eng"],"modified":"2024-01-31T09:48:22Z","published":"2022-01-01","publisher":"Lever Press","subject":["FICTION / Historical/Renaissance","FIC101000 FICTION / World Literature / France / General"]},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/fn107163j/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/fn107163j/download","type":"application/epub+zip"}],"images":[{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/8336h4532/full/full/0/default.jpg","type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/8336h4532/full/200,/0/default.jpg","width":200,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/8336h4532/full/400,/0/default.jpg","width":400,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/8336h4532/full/800,/0/default.jpg","width":800,"type":"image/jpeg"}]},{"metadata":{"@type":"http://schema.org/EBook","title":"Casa Pueblo: A Puerto Rican Model of Self-Governance","author":["González, Alexis Massol","Ravikumar, Ashwin","Schroeder Rodríguez, Paul"],"description":"\u003cdiv\u003eAs a community-based organization in the mountains of south-central Puerto Rico, Casa Pueblo implements alternatives to extractive capitalism that do not rely on governments or distant non-profits. In this book, Alexis Massol González, Casa Pueblo’s founder, reflects on its extraordinary forty-year history of experiments with community self-governance. Massol-González received the prestigious Goldman Prize (popularly known as the Green Nobel) for the organization’s initiatives to protect the environment, affirm cultural and human values, and create sustainable economic alternatives. This collective translation was undertaken in the spirit of the organization and offers a chronological account of Casa Pueblo’s evolution from a small group of concerned citizens to an internationally recognized model for activism.   \u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.12467264\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.12467264","language":"eng","modified":"2023-12-12T09:19:23Z","published":"2022-01-01","publisher":"Lever Press","subject":["SOCIAL SCIENCE   / Ethnic Studies/Caribbean \u0026 Latin American Studies","HISTORY   / Social History"]},"links":[{"rel":"self","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/gt54kq51z/download","type":"application/epub+zip"},{"rel":"http://opds-spec.org/acquisition/open-access","href":"https://www.fulcrum.org/ebooks/gt54kq51z/download","type":"application/epub+zip"}],"images":[{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/q811kn125/full/full/0/default.jpg","type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/q811kn125/full/200,/0/default.jpg","width":200,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/q811kn125/full/400,/0/default.jpg","width":400,"type":"image/jpeg"},{"href":"https://www.fulcrum.org//image-service/q811kn125/full/800,/0/default.jpg","width":800,"type":"image/jpeg"}]},{"metadata":{"@type":"http://schema.org/EBook","title":"Vinyl Theory","author":"Di Leo, Jeffrey R.","description":"\u003cdiv\u003eWhy are vinyl records making a comeback? How is their resurgence connected to the political economy of music? \u003cem\u003eVinyl Theory\u003c\/em\u003e responds to these and other questions by exploring the intersection of vinyl records with critical theory. In the process, it asks how the political economy of music might be connected with the philosophy of the record. The young critical theorist and composer Theodor Adorno’s work on the philosophy of the record and the political economy of music of the contemporary French public intellectual, Jacques Attali, are brought together with the work of other theorists to in order to understand the fall and resurrection of vinyl records. The major argument of \u003cem\u003eVinyl Theory\u003c\/em\u003e is that the very existence of vinyl records may be central to understanding the resiliency of neoliberalism. This argument is made by examining the work of Adorno, Attali, Friedrich Nietzsche, and others on music through the lens of Michel Foucault’s biopolitics.\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003cb\u003eReviews\u003c\/b\u003e\u003cbr\u003e \u0026quot;The disarming innocence of Di Leo\u0026#39;s memoir-esque reflections allow readers to feel the material conditions under which music is recorded, stored, distributed, and played. . . The book is a tightly syncopated composition that develops an answer to the puzzle of why vinyl is making a commercial come-back.\u0026quot;\u003cbr\u003e – \u003cem\u003eThe Comparatist\u003c\/em\u003e\u003c\/p\u003e \u003cp\u003e\u003cb\u003eAbout the author\u003c\/b\u003e\u003cbr\u003e Jeffrey R. Di Leo is a Professor of English and Philosophy at the University of Houston-Victoria.\u003cbr\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.11676127\"\u003eView on Fulcrum platform.\u003c\/a\u003e\u003c\/div\u003e","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.11676127","language":